# Incident Response
**Project:** {{ project_name }}

## Severity levels
| Level | Definition | Response time | Escalate to |
|-------|-----------|---------------|-------------|
| P1 | Total outage, data loss, security breach | Immediate | <!-- AI: on-call lead --> |
| P2 | Major feature broken for all users | < 30 min | <!-- AI: on-call lead --> |
| P3 | Feature broken for some users | < 2 hours | <!-- AI: team channel --> |
| P4 | Minor bug, workaround exists | Next business day | <!-- AI: issue tracker --> |

## Response steps (for any incident)
<!-- AI: Follow these in order. Do not skip steps. -->
1. Acknowledge: Post "I'm investigating [symptom]" in <!-- AI: incident channel -->
2. Assess severity using the table above.
3. If P1 or P2: immediately notify <!-- AI: on-call lead / team -->
4. Identify the proximate cause: recent deploy? Traffic spike? Upstream service failure?
5. **Mitigate first** — rollback if needed (see [15-RUNBOOK-DEPLOY.md](./15-RUNBOOK-DEPLOY.md)). Root cause second.
6. Post status updates every 15 minutes until resolved.
7. Write the incident report within 24 hours (template below).

## Common failure modes
<!-- AI: Fill this table as incidents occur. It grows over time. -->
| Symptom | Likely cause | First action |
|---------|-------------|-------------|
| API 500s spiking | Bad deploy or slow DB query | Check deploy logs, then slow query log |
| Auth / login broken | Auth service down or JWT secret rotated | Check auth service health, check secret age |
| Emails not sending | SMTP credentials expired or rate-limited | Check SMTP provider dashboard |
